metadata.name: MOMENT #29
metadata.description:
An endless row of them making up each life. Some poignant, some inspiring, some grievous, some affirming - but most of them a tad boring, a bit generic, almost forgettable like bland fabric. How can a life constructed from such mundanity count for anything? Maybe thanks to the last one, the one that stitches them all together, like a punchline to an absurdist joke.

Generative art written in JavaScript + Canvas with a little bit of help from p5.js.

metadata.description:
Touches innocent or intense, feeble connections made, group think enabled, outsiders outcast.

An experiment in gradient- and shading techniques, and restrictions of a flow field.
Written in JavaScript for Canvas.

metadata.name: Tintinnabulum #60
metadata.description:
An audiovisual collection.
.
Click to start the sound.
..
Tintinnabulum is an endless generative music player.
...
There are 8 color palettes which correlate with 8 different root notes (C, G, F, D, Bb, A, Eb, B).

5 Noise types correlate with 5 different scales (Minor, Hicaz, Major, Lydian, Locrian) which have 2 registers.

2 different rhythmical structures (Polyrhthmic & standart). Each has 4 divisions.

2 rotation options; On, Off.
....
Harmonization process based on Avro Part's 'Tintinnabuli' style.

Made with p5.js and Web Audio.

Ilgın İçözü, November 2021
@distcollective

metadata.name: Insula #42
metadata.description:
An audiovisual collection.
.
Click to start the sound.
..
Insula is an endless generative music player.
...
There are 6 different grid size; 4 squares and 20 squares are the rare ones.

2 different background texture; Lines, Grain.

2 different color placement; Circular, Linear.

7 different noise types.

8 different scales with fixed root notes; C Maj., C Lydian, D Dorian, D Min. Penta., G Maj., G Maj. Penta., F Mixolydian, F Min.

2 different rhythmical structures; 2:3, 4:5.

2 different note indicator style; Circle and Square. Square is rare and behaves differently.

5 different note indicator line divisions.
....
Harmonization process based on Avro Part's 'Tintinnabuli' style.

Grid design inspired from Novation's Launchpad.


Made with p5.js and Web Audio.

Ilgın İçözü, December 2021
@distcollective

metadata.name: Are you lucky? #3
metadata.description:
The more dots you see, the rarer it is.


There are twice as many tokens with 2 dots as with 4 dots.
There are twice as many tokens with 4 dots as with 8 dots.
There are twice as many tokens with 8 dots as with 16 dots.
...
There are twice as many tokens with 512 dots as with 1024 dots.

Good luck!


Made by Camille Roux (@camillerouxart)

metadata.name: BRIDGE #36
metadata.description:
BRIDGE is a collaborative project for fx(hash), conceived by Camille Roux. The project was announced on Twitter on Feb. 7, 2022 [1]. Artists were given two weeks to contribute code that would draw tiles representing a bridge, in their own style. Artists were free to implement their own artistic vision, subject to one simple constraint: Respect the coordinates of the tiles for each iteration of the art. 

Each iteration has a default style determined randomly at mint. This style is named in the features and displayed in the thumbnail. However, each iteration includes all styles, and you can cycle through them by clicking on or touching the image. Styles will be shown in the order in which they are listed under INCLUDED STYLES.

Press "s" to save a screenshot.

THE STORY

I'm Camille Roux. I planned to do a lot of collab this year with fx(hash) artists I like, but it takes too much time, or maybe I like too many artists :) Some days ago, I woke up with this idea in mind: "Hey! What if I make a collaboration with all the artists I like at once!" This is how the BRIDGE project was born.

Moreover, I love the mutual aid and solidarity between fx(hash) generative artists. The BRIDGE can be seen as a symbol of the link between us ♥️.

The project has also served as an inspiration for participants to extend and develop their coding skills outside their usual areas of interest. The code for the entire project remains available on GitHub [2].
